</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">The descending duodenum is a structure with distinct pathologic processes and anatomic relationships that requires a systematic approach to the differential diagnosis. Because of its tubular shape and fixed position in the retroperitoneum, both intrinsic duodenal and juxtaduodenal diseases are capable of producing luminal narrowing and obstruction. Duodenal lesions may be located in the mucosa or submucosa. Extraduodenal lesions may originate in adjacent structures—such as the pancreas, liver, gallbladder, colon, and lymph nodes—or from other retroperitoneal structures. Causes of duodenal obstruction include intraluminal masses, such as bezoars; duodenal inflammation, such as as peptic ulcers and Crohn disease; hematomas; and benign or malignant mucosal and intramural tumors. Pancreatic inflammation; tumors; and extrinsic compression caused by gallbladder processes, hepatic masses, retroperitoneal fluid collections, and tumors, including lymphoma, may produce duodenal obstruction. Abdominal radiography, barium studies, multidetector computed tomography, magnetic resonance imaging, and positron emission tomography may be used to depict and characterize duodenal strictures. Integration of imaging, clinical, laboratory, and endoscopic findings plays a major role in establishing a diagnosis of obstructive duodenal strictures.</div><div role="paragraph">©RSNA, 2014</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.345130055">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.345130055">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130055/asset/images/large/rg.345130055.fig1.jpeg" height="969" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig1" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1</span> The “double bubble” sign of duodenal obstruction. Abdominal radiograph obtained with the patient in an upright position shows two air bubbles with air-fluid levels, which correspond to the gastric fundus (arrowhead) and a dilated superior flexure of the duodenum (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130055&amp;id=fig1">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130055/asset/images/large/rg.345130055.fig2.jpeg" height="3412" width="3400" aria-labelledby="fig2" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2</span> Suggested diagnostic algorithm for evaluation of patients with duodenal strictures. <i>EUS</i> = endoscopic US, <i>GI</i> = gastrointestinal, <i>MDCT</i> = multidetector CT, <i>MRI</i> = MR imaging.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130055&amp;id=fig2">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130055/asset/images/large/rg.345130055.fig3a.jpeg" height="1025" width="559" aria-labelledby="fig3a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3a</span> Duodenal postbulbar ulcerations. <b>(a, b)</b> En face <b>(a)</b> and lateral <b>(b)</b> images from a double-contrast barium study show an acute ulcer niche in the proximal descending duodenum with a luminal stricture (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Coronal reformatted CT image shows the ulcer to be filled with air (arrow) and periduodenal inflammation. <b>(d)</b> Image from a barium study shows a short stricture in the descending duodenum with converging folds and no central deposition of contrast material (arrow), a result of a healed chronic ulcer. These findings are indicative of postbulbar duodenal ulcer scarring.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130055&amp;id=fig3a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130055/asset/images/large/rg.345130055.fig3b.jpeg" height="1025" width="769" aria-labelledby="fig3b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3b</span> Duodenal postbulbar ulcerations. <b>(a, b)</b> En face <b>(a)</b> and lateral <b>(b)</b> images from a double-contrast barium study show an acute ulcer niche in the proximal descending duodenum with a luminal stricture (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Coronal reformatted CT image shows the ulcer to be filled with air (arrow) and periduodenal inflammation. <b>(d)</b> Image from a barium study shows a short stricture in the descending duodenum with converging folds and no central deposition of contrast material (arrow), a result of a healed chronic ulcer. These findings are indicative of postbulbar duodenal ulcer scarring.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130055&amp;id=fig3b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130055/asset/images/large/rg.345130055.fig3c.jpeg" height="899" width="842" aria-labelledby="fig3c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3c</span> Duodenal postbulbar ulcerations. <b>(a, b)</b> En face <b>(a)</b> and lateral <b>(b)</b> images from a double-contrast barium study show an acute ulcer niche in the proximal descending duodenum with a luminal stricture (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Coronal reformatted CT image shows the ulcer to be filled with air (arrow) and periduodenal inflammation. <b>(d)</b> Image from a barium study shows a short stricture in the descending duodenum with converging folds and no central deposition of contrast material (arrow), a result of a healed chronic ulcer. These findings are indicative of postbulbar duodenal ulcer scarring.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130055&amp;id=fig3c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130055/asset/images/large/rg.345130055.fig3d.jpeg" height="899" width="633" aria-labelledby="fig3d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3d</span> Duodenal postbulbar ulcerations. <b>(a, b)</b> En face <b>(a)</b> and lateral <b>(b)</b> images from a double-contrast barium study show an acute ulcer niche in the proximal descending duodenum with a luminal stricture (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Coronal reformatted CT image shows the ulcer to be filled with air (arrow) and periduodenal inflammation. <b>(d)</b> Image from a barium study shows a short stricture in the descending duodenum with converging folds and no central deposition of contrast material (arrow), a result of a healed chronic ulcer. These findings are indicative of postbulbar duodenal ulcer scarring.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130055&amp;id=fig3d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130055/asset/images/large/rg.345130055.fig4a.jpeg" height="856" width="674" aria-labelledby="fig4a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4a</span> Disseminated histoplasmosis. <b>(a)</b> Image from a single-contrast barium study shows a tapered stricture in the distal descending duodenum with irregular mucosal folds resulting from inflammation (arrow). The differential diagnosis for these findings includes Zollinger-Ellison syndrome, acute pancreatitis, and Crohn disease. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image shows mural thickening in the lower descending duodenum (arrow) and an adjacent fluid collection (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130055&amp;id=fig4a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130055/asset/images/large/rg.345130055.fig4b.jpeg" height="856" width="1002" aria-labelledby="fig4b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4b</span> Disseminated histoplasmosis. <b>(a)</b> Image from a single-contrast barium study shows a tapered stricture in the distal descending duodenum with irregular mucosal folds resulting from inflammation (arrow). The differential diagnosis for these findings includes Zollinger-Ellison syndrome, acute pancreatitis, and Crohn disease. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image shows mural thickening in the lower descending duodenum (arrow) and an adjacent fluid collection (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130055&amp;id=fig4b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130055/asset/images/large/rg.345130055.fig5a.jpeg" height="938" width="755" aria-labelledby="fig5a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5a</span> Duodenal Crohn disease in three patients. <b>(a)</b> Image from a single-contrast barium study shows multiple strictures in the duodenal bulb (*) and descending duodenum (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Spot image from a barium study performed in a different patient shows severe narrowing of the descending duodenum (arrowheads) and a linear longitudinal ulcer in the inferior flexure (arrows) surrounded by radiolucent lines of edema. Note the sacculation <i>(S)</i> in the opposite wall. <b>(c)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image obtained in a third patient shows the thickened and hyperemic wall of the distal descending and third portions of the duodenum (arrow) and periduodenal fat stranding (arrowheads).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130055&amp;id=fig5a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130055/asset/images/large/rg.345130055.fig5b.jpeg" height="938" width="818" aria-labelledby="fig5b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5b</span> Duodenal Crohn disease in three patients. <b>(a)</b> Image from a single-contrast barium study shows multiple strictures in the duodenal bulb (*) and descending duodenum (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Spot image from a barium study performed in a different patient shows severe narrowing of the descending duodenum (arrowheads) and a linear longitudinal ulcer in the inferior flexure (arrows) surrounded by radiolucent lines of edema. Note the sacculation <i>(S)</i> in the opposite wall. <b>(c)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image obtained in a third patient shows the thickened and hyperemic wall of the distal descending and third portions of the duodenum (arrow) and periduodenal fat stranding (arrowheads).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130055&amp;id=fig5b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130055/asset/images/large/rg.345130055.fig5c.jpeg" height="568" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig5c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5c</span> Duodenal Crohn disease in three patients. <b>(a)</b> Image from a single-contrast barium study shows multiple strictures in the duodenal bulb (*) and descending duodenum (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Spot image from a barium study performed in a different patient shows severe narrowing of the descending duodenum (arrowheads) and a linear longitudinal ulcer in the inferior flexure (arrows) surrounded by radiolucent lines of edema. Note the sacculation <i>(S)</i> in the opposite wall. <b>(c)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image obtained in a third patient shows the thickened and hyperemic wall of the distal descending and third portions of the duodenum (arrow) and periduodenal fat stranding (arrowheads).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130055&amp;id=fig5c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130055/asset/images/large/rg.345130055.fig6a.jpeg" height="880" width="498" aria-labelledby="fig6a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6a</span> Duodenal polyps. <b>(a)</b> Image from a contrast-enhanced barium study shows a pedunculated polyp (arrow) in the lumen of the descending duodenum. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image shows the head of a pedunculated polyp (arrow) partially occupying the lumen of the descending duodenum.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130055&amp;id=fig6a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130055/asset/images/large/rg.345130055.fig6b.jpeg" height="880" width="974" aria-labelledby="fig6b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6b</span> Duodenal polyps. <b>(a)</b> Image from a contrast-enhanced barium study shows a pedunculated polyp (arrow) in the lumen of the descending duodenum. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image shows the head of a pedunculated polyp (arrow) partially occupying the lumen of the descending duodenum.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130055&amp;id=fig6b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130055/asset/images/large/rg.345130055.fig7a.jpeg" height="1032" width="690" aria-labelledby="fig7a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7a</span> Villous adenoma in two patients. <b>(a)</b> Image from a barium study shows a sessile intraluminal filling defect with a typical lobulated frond-like surface pattern (arrows) originating from the medial wall of the descending duodenum adjacent to papilla. <b>(b)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced reconstructed CT image obtained in a different patient shows a large intraluminal filling defect originating from the medial wall of the descending duodenum (arrowheads), compressing the papilla, and dilating the biliary system (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130055&amp;id=fig7a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130055/asset/images/large/rg.345130055.fig7b.jpeg" height="1032" width="785" aria-labelledby="fig7b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7b</span> Villous adenoma in two patients. <b>(a)</b> Image from a barium study shows a sessile intraluminal filling defect with a typical lobulated frond-like surface pattern (arrows) originating from the medial wall of the descending duodenum adjacent to papilla. <b>(b)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced reconstructed CT image obtained in a different patient shows a large intraluminal filling defect originating from the medial wall of the descending duodenum (arrowheads), compressing the papilla, and dilating the biliary system (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130055&amp;id=fig7b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130055/asset/images/large/rg.345130055.fig8.jpeg" height="950" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig8" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8</span> Multiple vascular hemangiomas. Image from a barium study shows multiple polypoid lesions with an irregular mucosal surface (arrows) occupying the lumen of the descending duodenum. A biliary stent placed to release the stricture of the biliary ductal system, which was caused by the polyps, is seen. Multiple villous adenomas may have a similar appearance.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130055&amp;id=fig8">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130055/asset/images/large/rg.345130055.fig9.jpeg" height="998" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig9" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9</span> Benign GIST. Spot image from a double-contrast barium study shows a submucosal mass with normal mucosa (arrowheads) en face in the distal descending duodenum.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130055&amp;id=fig9">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130055/asset/images/large/rg.345130055.fig10a.jpeg" height="716" width="761" aria-labelledby="fig10a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10a</span> Malignant duodenal GIST. <b>(a)</b> Image from a barium study shows an ulcerated submucosal mass in the inferior flexure of the duodenum (arrow) with widening of the duodenal C-loop (arrowheads), a result of extrinsic compression by a tumor. <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a large ulcerated duodenal mass (arrow) with compression and lateral displacement of the duodenal lumen (arrowhead). This imaging pattern may resemble that of pseudoaneurysmatic dilatation of the duodenal lumen in lymphoma. <b>(c)</b> Photograph of the gross specimen shows a submucosal obstructing mass with areas of intralesional hemorrhage. (Scale is in centimeters.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130055&amp;id=fig10a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130055/asset/images/large/rg.345130055.fig10b.jpeg" height="716" width="702" aria-labelledby="fig10b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10b</span> Malignant duodenal GIST. <b>(a)</b> Image from a barium study shows an ulcerated submucosal mass in the inferior flexure of the duodenum (arrow) with widening of the duodenal C-loop (arrowheads), a result of extrinsic compression by a tumor. <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a large ulcerated duodenal mass (arrow) with compression and lateral displacement of the duodenal lumen (arrowhead). This imaging pattern may resemble that of pseudoaneurysmatic dilatation of the duodenal lumen in lymphoma. <b>(c)</b> Photograph of the gross specimen shows a submucosal obstructing mass with areas of intralesional hemorrhage. (Scale is in centimeters.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130055&amp;id=fig10b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130055/asset/images/large/rg.345130055.fig10c.jpeg" height="656" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig10c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10c</span> Malignant duodenal GIST. <b>(a)</b> Image from a barium study shows an ulcerated submucosal mass in the inferior flexure of the duodenum (arrow) with widening of the duodenal C-loop (arrowheads), a result of extrinsic compression by a tumor. <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a large ulcerated duodenal mass (arrow) with compression and lateral displacement of the duodenal lumen (arrowhead). This imaging pattern may resemble that of pseudoaneurysmatic dilatation of the duodenal lumen in lymphoma. <b>(c)</b> Photograph of the gross specimen shows a submucosal obstructing mass with areas of intralesional hemorrhage. (Scale is in centimeters.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130055&amp;id=fig10c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130055/asset/images/large/rg.345130055.fig11a.jpeg" height="786" width="580" aria-labelledby="fig11a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11a</span> Duodenal lipomas in two patients. <b>(a)</b> Image from a barium study shows a large filling defect with normal mucosa (arrows) in the medial wall of the descending duodenum. <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image obtained in a different patient shows a small intramural tumor with uniform fat attenuation (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130055&amp;id=fig11a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130055/asset/images/large/rg.345130055.fig11b.jpeg" height="786" width="893" aria-labelledby="fig11b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11b</span> Duodenal lipomas in two patients. <b>(a)</b> Image from a barium study shows a large filling defect with normal mucosa (arrows) in the medial wall of the descending duodenum. <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image obtained in a different patient shows a small intramural tumor with uniform fat attenuation (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130055&amp;id=fig11b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130055/asset/images/large/rg.345130055.fig12a.jpeg" height="883" width="572" aria-labelledby="fig12a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12a</span> Duodenal carcinoma. <b>(a)</b> Image from a double-contrast barium study shows a typical “apple-core” lesion in the descending duodenum (arrow), which is characterized by shouldering and irregular mucosa with filling defects and ulcerations. <b>(b)</b> FDG PET/CT image shows an FDG-avid lesion in the descending duodenum (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130055&amp;id=fig12a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130055/asset/images/large/rg.345130055.fig12b.jpeg" height="883" width="905" aria-labelledby="fig12b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12b</span> Duodenal carcinoma. <b>(a)</b> Image from a double-contrast barium study shows a typical “apple-core” lesion in the descending duodenum (arrow), which is characterized by shouldering and irregular mucosa with filling defects and ulcerations. <b>(b)</b> FDG PET/CT image shows an FDG-avid lesion in the descending duodenum (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130055&amp;id=fig12b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130055/asset/images/large/rg.345130055.fig13a.jpeg" height="994" width="678" aria-labelledby="fig13a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13a</span> Polypoid periampullary carcinoma in two patients. <b>(a, b)</b> Spot images from a double-contrast barium study of the descending duodenum show a broad-based mass with normal mucosa arising from the medial duodenal wall (arrows), a finding consistent with a submucosal mass. The tumor originates in the ductal side of the ampulla. <b>(c)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image obtained in a different patient shows an ampullary tumor as a small filling defect protruding into the duodenal lumen (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130055&amp;id=fig13a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130055/asset/images/large/rg.345130055.fig13b.jpeg" height="994" width="647" aria-labelledby="fig13b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13b</span> Polypoid periampullary carcinoma in two patients. <b>(a, b)</b> Spot images from a double-contrast barium study of the descending duodenum show a broad-based mass with normal mucosa arising from the medial duodenal wall (arrows), a finding consistent with a submucosal mass. The tumor originates in the ductal side of the ampulla. <b>(c)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image obtained in a different patient shows an ampullary tumor as a small filling defect protruding into the duodenal lumen (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130055&amp;id=fig13b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130055/asset/images/large/rg.345130055.fig13c.jpeg" height="762" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig13c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13c</span> Polypoid periampullary carcinoma in two patients. <b>(a, b)</b> Spot images from a double-contrast barium study of the descending duodenum show a broad-based mass with normal mucosa arising from the medial duodenal wall (arrows), a finding consistent with a submucosal mass. The tumor originates in the ductal side of the ampulla. <b>(c)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image obtained in a different patient shows an ampullary tumor as a small filling defect protruding into the duodenal lumen (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130055&amp;id=fig13c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130055/asset/images/large/rg.345130055.fig14a.jpeg" height="1003" width="747" aria-labelledby="fig14a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14a</span> Infiltrating periampullary carcinoma. <b>(a)</b> Spot image from a double-contrast barium study shows circumferential narrowing of the descending duodenum with an irregularity in the mucosal surface that is more widespread on the medial wall (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Photograph of the gross specimen shows the mass surrounding the main duodenal papilla (arrows). Arrowhead = minor papilla.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130055&amp;id=fig14a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130055/asset/images/large/rg.345130055.fig14b.jpeg" height="1003" width="727" aria-labelledby="fig14b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14b</span> Infiltrating periampullary carcinoma. <b>(a)</b> Spot image from a double-contrast barium study shows circumferential narrowing of the descending duodenum with an irregularity in the mucosal surface that is more widespread on the medial wall (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Photograph of the gross specimen shows the mass surrounding the main duodenal papilla (arrows). Arrowhead = minor papilla.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130055&amp;id=fig14b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130055/asset/images/large/rg.345130055.fig15a.jpeg" height="715" width="680" aria-labelledby="fig15a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15a</span> Duodenal hematoma seen as an intraluminal filling defect. <b>(a)</b> Image from a barium study shows a dilated proximal duodenum with a large intraluminal filling defect (*).The barium in the periphery of the lumen demonstrates a normal mucosal pattern (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a mass with slightly high attenuation (59 HU) occupying a dilated duodenal lumen (*). Duodenal mucosal hyperemia is also seen (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130055&amp;id=fig15a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130055/asset/images/large/rg.345130055.fig15b.jpeg" height="715" width="795" aria-labelledby="fig15b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15b</span> Duodenal hematoma seen as an intraluminal filling defect. <b>(a)</b> Image from a barium study shows a dilated proximal duodenum with a large intraluminal filling defect (*).The barium in the periphery of the lumen demonstrates a normal mucosal pattern (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a mass with slightly high attenuation (59 HU) occupying a dilated duodenal lumen (*). Duodenal mucosal hyperemia is also seen (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130055&amp;id=fig15b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130055/asset/images/large/rg.345130055.fig16.jpeg" height="1050" width="700" aria-labelledby="fig16" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16</span> Duodenal hematoma compressing the lumen. Image from a single-contrast barium study shows circumferential narrowing of the descending duodenum (arrows), with the transition point at the duodenal bulb.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130055&amp;id=fig16">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130055/asset/images/large/rg.345130055.fig17a.jpeg" height="814" width="595" aria-labelledby="fig17a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17a</span> Duodenal involvement by acute pancreatitis. <b>(a)</b> Image from a single-contrast barium study shows a widened duodenal C-loop with thickened folds. <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows lateral displacement of the descending duodenum (arrow), a result of a peripancreatic fluid collection, which is secondary to necrotizing acute pancreatitis. Hyperemia and thickening of the duodenal wall (arrowhead) are also seen.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130055&amp;id=fig17a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130055/asset/images/large/rg.345130055.fig17b.jpeg" height="814" width="1079" aria-labelledby="fig17b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17b</span> Duodenal involvement by acute pancreatitis. <b>(a)</b> Image from a single-contrast barium study shows a widened duodenal C-loop with thickened folds. <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows lateral displacement of the descending duodenum (arrow), a result of a peripancreatic fluid collection, which is secondary to necrotizing acute pancreatitis. Hyperemia and thickening of the duodenal wall (arrowhead) are also seen.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130055&amp;id=fig17b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130055/asset/images/large/rg.345130055.fig18a.jpeg" height="883" width="747" aria-labelledby="fig18a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18a</span> Duodenal compression by pancreatic pseudocysts. <b>(a)</b> Image from a barium study shows widening of the duodenal sweep and extrinsic compression of the greater curvature and proximal duodenum (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Reformatted coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows lateral displacement of the descending duodenum (arrow) by the pancreatic pseudocyst.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130055&amp;id=fig18a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130055/asset/images/large/rg.345130055.fig18b.jpeg" height="883" width="925" aria-labelledby="fig18b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18b</span> Duodenal compression by pancreatic pseudocysts. <b>(a)</b> Image from a barium study shows widening of the duodenal sweep and extrinsic compression of the greater curvature and proximal duodenum (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Reformatted coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows lateral displacement of the descending duodenum (arrow) by the pancreatic pseudocyst.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130055&amp;id=fig18b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130055/asset/images/large/rg.345130055.fig19a.jpeg" height="686" width="861" aria-labelledby="fig19a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19a</span> Duodenal gastrinoma. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial <b>(a)</b> and reconstructed coronal <b>(b)</b> contrast-enhanced arterial phase CT images show a round hypervascular lesion in the wall of the descending duodenum (arrow) and opacification of the duodenal lumen with positive gastrointestinal contrast material. <b>(c)</b> Photograph of the gross specimen confirms the presence of a tumor in the duodenal wall (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130055&amp;id=fig19a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130055/asset/images/large/rg.345130055.fig19b.jpeg" height="686" width="614" aria-labelledby="fig19b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19b</span> Duodenal gastrinoma. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial <b>(a)</b> and reconstructed coronal <b>(b)</b> contrast-enhanced arterial phase CT images show a round hypervascular lesion in the wall of the descending duodenum (arrow) and opacification of the duodenal lumen with positive gastrointestinal contrast material. <b>(c)</b> Photograph of the gross specimen confirms the presence of a tumor in the duodenal wall (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130055&amp;id=fig19b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130055/asset/images/large/rg.345130055.fig19c.jpeg" height="675" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig19c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19c</span> Duodenal gastrinoma. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial <b>(a)</b> and reconstructed coronal <b>(b)</b> contrast-enhanced arterial phase CT images show a round hypervascular lesion in the wall of the descending duodenum (arrow) and opacification of the duodenal lumen with positive gastrointestinal contrast material. <b>(c)</b> Photograph of the gross specimen confirms the presence of a tumor in the duodenal wall (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130055&amp;id=fig19c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130055/asset/images/large/rg.345130055.fig20a.jpeg" height="724" width="898" aria-labelledby="fig20a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20a</span> Pancreatic solid pseudopapillary tumor. <b>(a)</b> Axial T2-weighted MR image shows an encapsulated heterogeneous mass with multiple cystic foci in the pancreatic head (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Photograph of the gross specimen shows a circumscribed encapsulated mass with firm tan-gray areas, yellow foci of necrosis, and red areas of hemorrhage.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130055&amp;id=fig20a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130055/asset/images/large/rg.345130055.fig20b.jpeg" height="724" width="575" aria-labelledby="fig20b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20b</span> Pancreatic solid pseudopapillary tumor. <b>(a)</b> Axial T2-weighted MR image shows an encapsulated heterogeneous mass with multiple cystic foci in the pancreatic head (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Photograph of the gross specimen shows a circumscribed encapsulated mass with firm tan-gray areas, yellow foci of necrosis, and red areas of hemorrhage.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130055&amp;id=fig20b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130055/asset/images/large/rg.345130055.fig21a.jpeg" height="746" width="637" aria-labelledby="fig21a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21a</span> Duodenal infiltration by pancreatic carcinoma. <b>(a)</b> Image from a single-contrast barium study of the descending duodenum shows an area of luminal narrowing with irregular mucosa (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows an irregular stricture in the descending duodenum (arrow) adjacent to a pancreatic head mass (*). Parenchymal atrophy and dilatation of the main pancreatic duct in the body of the pancreas (arrowhead) are also seen. <b>(c)</b> Axial fused PET/CT image shows intensely FDG-avid lesions in the pancreatic head (arrow) and adjacent duodenum (arrowhead), a result of infiltration. <b>(d)</b> Photograph of the gross specimen shows a firm yellow-gray tumor involving the pancreatic head (*), infiltrating the duodenal muscle layer, and compressing the duodenum (arrows). (Scale is in centimeters.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130055&amp;id=fig21a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130055/asset/images/large/rg.345130055.fig21b.jpeg" height="746" width="1042" aria-labelledby="fig21b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21b</span> Duodenal infiltration by pancreatic carcinoma. <b>(a)</b> Image from a single-contrast barium study of the descending duodenum shows an area of luminal narrowing with irregular mucosa (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows an irregular stricture in the descending duodenum (arrow) adjacent to a pancreatic head mass (*). Parenchymal atrophy and dilatation of the main pancreatic duct in the body of the pancreas (arrowhead) are also seen. <b>(c)</b> Axial fused PET/CT image shows intensely FDG-avid lesions in the pancreatic head (arrow) and adjacent duodenum (arrowhead), a result of infiltration. <b>(d)</b> Photograph of the gross specimen shows a firm yellow-gray tumor involving the pancreatic head (*), infiltrating the duodenal muscle layer, and compressing the duodenum (arrows). (Scale is in centimeters.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130055&amp;id=fig21b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130055/asset/images/large/rg.345130055.fig21c.jpeg" height="620" width="870" aria-labelledby="fig21c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21c</span> Duodenal infiltration by pancreatic carcinoma. <b>(a)</b> Image from a single-contrast barium study of the descending duodenum shows an area of luminal narrowing with irregular mucosa (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows an irregular stricture in the descending duodenum (arrow) adjacent to a pancreatic head mass (*). Parenchymal atrophy and dilatation of the main pancreatic duct in the body of the pancreas (arrowhead) are also seen. <b>(c)</b> Axial fused PET/CT image shows intensely FDG-avid lesions in the pancreatic head (arrow) and adjacent duodenum (arrowhead), a result of infiltration. <b>(d)</b> Photograph of the gross specimen shows a firm yellow-gray tumor involving the pancreatic head (*), infiltrating the duodenal muscle layer, and compressing the duodenum (arrows). (Scale is in centimeters.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130055&amp;id=fig21c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130055/asset/images/large/rg.345130055.fig21d.jpeg" height="620" width="907" aria-labelledby="fig21d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21d</span> Duodenal infiltration by pancreatic carcinoma. <b>(a)</b> Image from a single-contrast barium study of the descending duodenum shows an area of luminal narrowing with irregular mucosa (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows an irregular stricture in the descending duodenum (arrow) adjacent to a pancreatic head mass (*). Parenchymal atrophy and dilatation of the main pancreatic duct in the body of the pancreas (arrowhead) are also seen. <b>(c)</b> Axial fused PET/CT image shows intensely FDG-avid lesions in the pancreatic head (arrow) and adjacent duodenum (arrowhead), a result of infiltration. <b>(d)</b> Photograph of the gross specimen shows a firm yellow-gray tumor involving the pancreatic head (*), infiltrating the duodenal muscle layer, and compressing the duodenum (arrows). (Scale is in centimeters.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130055&amp;id=fig21d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig22" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130055/asset/images/large/rg.345130055.fig22.jpeg" height="698" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig22" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22</span> Liver mass. Axial unenhanced CT image shows a metastasis from endometrial sarcoma (*) in the right hepatic lobe anteriorly and medially displacing the descending duodenum (arrow) and the pancreatic head <i>(P)</i>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130055&amp;id=fig22">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig23a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130055/asset/images/large/rg.345130055.fig23a.jpeg" height="710" width="656" aria-labelledby="fig23a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 23a</span> Duodenal compromise from an enlarged gallbladder in two patients. <b>(a)</b> Image from a barium study shows an extrinsic impression (arrows) in the duodenal cap and the lateral wall of the proximal descending duodenum, a result of an enlarged gallbladder. <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image obtained in a different patient with acute cholecystitis shows compression of the duodenum (arrowhead) by an enlarged gallbladder (*) and pancreatic calcifications (arrow), a result of underlying chronic pancreatitis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130055&amp;id=fig23a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig23b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130055/asset/images/large/rg.345130055.fig23b.jpeg" height="710" width="821" aria-labelledby="fig23b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 23b</span> Duodenal compromise from an enlarged gallbladder in two patients. <b>(a)</b> Image from a barium study shows an extrinsic impression (arrows) in the duodenal cap and the lateral wall of the proximal descending duodenum, a result of an enlarged gallbladder. <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image obtained in a different patient with acute cholecystitis shows compression of the duodenum (arrowhead) by an enlarged gallbladder (*) and pancreatic calcifications (arrow), a result of underlying chronic pancreatitis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130055&amp;id=fig23b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig24" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130055/asset/images/large/rg.345130055.fig24.jpeg" height="684" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig24" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 24</span> Crohn colitis. Axial unenhanced CT image shows mural thickening and luminal distention of the hepatic flexure of the colon (*), which is compressing the descending duodenum (arrow), and hypervascularity of pericolic fat and mesentery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130055&amp;id=fig24">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig25" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130055/asset/images/large/rg.345130055.fig25.jpeg" height="688" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig25" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 25</span> Periduodenal hematoma. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a periduodenal fluid collection with high attenuation (arrowheads) compressing the duodenal lumen (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130055&amp;id=fig25">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig26a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130055/asset/images/large/rg.345130055.fig26a.jpeg" height="746" width="530" aria-labelledby="fig26a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 26a</span> Retroperitoneal lymphoma. <b>(a)</b> Image from a single-contrast barium study shows a stricture in the descending duodenum with a normal mucosal pattern (arrow), a result of asymmetric duodenal mural compression. <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image obtained in the venous phase shows a large mass with soft-tissue attenuation in the anterior pararenal space interposed between the pancreas <i>(P)</i> and the displaced descending duodenum (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130055&amp;id=fig26a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig26b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130055/asset/images/large/rg.345130055.fig26b.jpeg" height="746" width="946" aria-labelledby="fig26b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 26b</span> Retroperitoneal lymphoma. <b>(a)</b> Image from a single-contrast barium study shows a stricture in the descending duodenum with a normal mucosal pattern (arrow), a result of asymmetric duodenal mural compression. <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image obtained in the venous phase shows a large mass with soft-tissue attenuation in the anterior pararenal space interposed between the pancreas <i>(P)</i> and the displaced descending duodenum (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130055&amp;id=fig26b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig27a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130055/asset/images/large/rg.345130055.fig27a.jpeg" height="832" width="911" aria-labelledby="fig27a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 27a</span> Retroperitoenal malignant fibrous histiocytoma. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a heterogeneous mass with calcifications in the anterior pararenal space (*) compressing and laterally displacing the duodenum (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Photograph of the gross specimen shows a gray-white mass with yellow nodular areas.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130055&amp;id=fig27a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig27b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130055/asset/images/large/rg.345130055.fig27b.jpeg" height="832" width="563" aria-labelledby="fig27b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 27b</span> Retroperitoenal malignant fibrous histiocytoma. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a heterogeneous mass with calcifications in the anterior pararenal space (*) compressing and laterally displacing the duodenum (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Photograph of the gross specimen shows a gray-white mass with yellow nodular areas.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130055&amp;id=fig27b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig28a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130055/asset/images/large/rg.345130055.fig28a.jpeg" height="732" width="849" aria-labelledby="fig28a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 28a</span> Trichobezoar. <b>(a)</b> Axial unenhanced CT image shows a dilated gastric and duodenal lumen (arrow) secondary to a heterogeneous mass with air contents. <b>(b)</b> Photograph of the gross specimen shows a mass of matted hair with food debris and mucus.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130055&amp;id=fig28a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig28b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130055/asset/images/large/rg.345130055.fig28b.jpeg" height="732" width="727" aria-labelledby="fig28b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 28b</span> Trichobezoar. <b>(a)</b> Axial unenhanced CT image shows a dilated gastric and duodenal lumen (arrow) secondary to a heterogeneous mass with air contents. <b>(b)</b> Photograph of the gross specimen shows a mass of matted hair with food debris and mucus.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130055&amp;id=fig28b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Laufer I, Levine S. Barium studies: principles of double-contrast diagnosis. In: Gore RM, Levine MS, eds. <em>Textbook of gastrointestinal radiology</em>. 3rd ed. Philadelphia, Pa: Saunders-Elsevier, 2008;37–69.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/B978-1-4160-2332-6.50009-9">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Barium+studies%3A+principles+of+double-contrast+diagnosis&amp;author=I+Laufer&amp;author=S+Levine&amp;publication_year=2008&amp;pages=37-69&amp;doi=10.1016%2FB978-1-4160-2332-6.50009-9">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">2.</div><div id="r2" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div cla